column207: i tried to think what the other player would do and use that as a safety net.  if i had A or B  and A is lower than sure payoff for both of us  i would say yes if B is higher.
If I was risking more than 5 points in a game  I would not play unless the other person was assured a zero for my worse case.
If there are two states possible  then I will sum up the payoff of the two states  and compare that with 2  | times the sure payoff.

if i was in a sure state  i chose the state with more points |  | if i was in an unsure state  i valued risking the difference between the sure and the low state with the sure and the high state.   |  | i would not risk 10 to win 5.  but i would risk 5 to win 10. |  | it took a few games before i followed this strategy.
If I knew the state for sure I decided to play only if the earnings were higher than the sure payoff.  If there were 2 possible states I only played if I couldn't lose more than 10 dollars.
I tried to play smart and not take too many chances

I looked at the optimal move of the other player based on his payoffs and tried to eliminate the cases for which he would play the game. I would then look at the remaining cases and determine if the payoff from those cases was higher than my sure payoff.

Always try to figure out what the other person might be told.  Using their best strategy  assuming they only think of themselves  and then plan my move based on what they should do. |  | This was all thrown out the window  of course  if the amont was revealed to me.  Then it was just a crass value-based decision.

you can tell if the other person will pick no if the payoff is higher than an assured state.  That allows you to be more risky if that state is also a bad state for you (lower than sure payoff).   |  | If that person will 100% say no to one state but yes to the other and that other state benefits you  then you can always say yes. because the other player will assuredly say no if the state is bad for you  so there is no risk to saying yes. |  | worse case- you play the game but the other player plays too because he knows the state for sure and that state leaves you with a lower than sure payoff- then it is up to chance.

I looked at the pay-offs for each of the boxes and tried to figure out in which cases the opposing player would want to play the game and in which he/she wouldn't. Based on that  I would make a decision whether it would make sense for me to play the game or not.
Compared the differences between the possibilities and the sure payoff.
